antic Rim, these were independent national societies whose cultural self-image was nevertheless marked by a sense of difference. Barshay presents a historical overview of major Japanese trends and treats two of the most powerful streams of Japanese social science, one associated with Marxism, the other with Modernism (kindaishugi), whose most representative figure is the late Maruyama Masao. Demonstrating that a sense of developmental alienation shaped the thinking of social scientists in both streams, the author argues that they provided Japanese social science with moments of shared self-understanding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aDemocracyxHistoryxJapan. 0aDemocracyzJapanxHistory. 0aIntellectualsxHistoryxJapan. 0aIntellectualszJapanxHistory. 0aPolitical culturexHistoryxJapanxJapan. 0aPolitical culturezJapanxHistory. 0aSocial sciencesxHistoryxJapan. 0aSocial scienceszJapanxHistory. 0aSocialismxHistoryxJapan. 0aSocialismzJapanxHistory. 0aSocialismzJapan. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520941335423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520941335.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles